But instead, the editor has created an incorrect structure where the `<ul>` is nested INSIDE the `<h1>` element:
```html
<h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Hello Jodit World!</li>
  </ul>
</h1>
```

This is invalid HTML - `<ul>` elements should not be children of `<h1>` elements. When the unordered list command is applied to an H1 element, the editor should convert the H1 to a list item or unwrap the H1, but instead it's nesting the `<ul>` inside the `<h1>`, which is incorrect behavior.

**Bug Report Summary:**

**Test performed:** Applied unordered list (ul) command to a Heading 1 (H1) element in the Jodit editor.

**Steps taken:**
1. ✅ Selected "Hello Jodit World!" text with Cmd+A
2. ✅ Clicked paragraph format dropdown and selected "Heading 1" - text became H1
3. ✅ Used Cmd+A again to select the H1 text
4. ✅ Clicked the "Insert Unordered List" button
5. ✅ Clicked the Source/HTML button (<>) to view source code

**Expected HTML result:**
```html
<ul><li>Hello Jodit World!</li></ul>
```

**Actual HTML result (BUG):**
```html
<h1>
  <ul>
    <li>Hello Jodit World!</li>
  </ul>
</h1>
```

**Bug:** When applying the "Insert Unordered List" command to text formatted as H1 (Heading 1), the Jodit editor incorrectly nests the `<ul>` element INSIDE the `<h1>` element, producing invalid HTML (`<h1><ul><li>text</li></ul></h1>`). The correct behavior should produce `<ul><li>text</li></ul>` (with the H1 formatting removed or the content moved outside the heading).

This is a **functional bug** in the Jodit editor - the list insertion command does not correctly handle the case when the selected text is inside a heading element. Instead of unwrapping the heading and creating a proper list, it nests the list inside the heading, creating invalid HTML structure.
